Let’s see confusion matrix for training set using typical cut-off point:

# let's see how our model predicts defaulting entities
predict <- predict(model_lr, type = 'response', newdata = train)

table(train$loan_status, predict > 0.5)
##    
##     FALSE  TRUE
##   0 12859   649
##   1  1624  2043

The results are not satisfactory, especially the number of the default customers assigned by the model to a non-default group is very high (1624). Banks cannot afford so many mistakes, therefore such a model must be either thoroughly corrected or rejected. This can be done by excluding not significant variables or changing the cut-off point.

The 2nd approach can be checked using ROC curve. Such a plot depicts how does the relation between true positive and false positive ratio changes while changing the cut-off point.

Then area under ROC-curve is measured. The most desired outcome would be one - that would mean that our model fetched all true - positive customers and no false positive ones.

ROCpred <- prediction(predict, train$loan_status)
ROCperf <- performance(ROCpred, 'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(ROCperf)

# AUC value
auc <- performance(ROCpred, measure = "auc")
auc <- auc@y.values[[1]]
auc
## [1] 0.8767559

The result is quite satisfactory.

Let’s see how that changes on testing sample:

Regarding the last task to do, I will choose the random forest model (as it gave the best AUC outcome) and try to estimate the model choosing the cut off-point, for which the ROC curve is closest to the upper left corner on the plot. Let’s have a look at this plot one more time:

ROCpred_t <- prediction(predict_RF, test$loan_status)
ROCperf_t <- performance(ROCpred_t, 'tpr', 'fpr')
plot(ROCperf_t)

I will use the function found on the internet to find the point on the ROC curve, which satisfies the condition mentioned above.

(source: https://www.r-bloggers.com/2014/12/a-small-introduction-to-the-rocr-package/)

opt.cut = function(perf, pred){
    cut.ind = mapply(FUN=function(x, y, p){
        d = (x - 0)^2 + (y-1)^2
        ind = which(d == min(d))
        c(sensitivity = y[[ind]], specificity = 1-x[[ind]], 
            cutoff = p[[ind]])
    }, perf@x.values, perf@y.values, pred@cutoffs)
}
print(opt.cut(ROCperf_t, ROCpred_t))
##                  [,1]
## sensitivity 0.7692308
## specificity 0.8759533
## cutoff      0.2003425
table(test$loan_status, predict_RF > 0.2003425)

##     FALSE TRUE
##   0  7810 1106
##   1   585 1950
